INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(695,1,'In a large saucepan, heat oil over medium heat.  Add veggies and garlic and saute for about 3 minutes.  Transfer to bowl.  Add miso.  Slowly add stock while stirring well.  Add parsley, veggies and pasta.  Toss and serve.  Add more liquid if too thick.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(695,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(695,3,'From Bruce Jacobs, Head Chef of Bristol Farms Typed for you by Karen Mintzias');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(696,1,'Soak beans in cold water to cover overnight. Drain off water. Add 3 cups fresh water to beans and cook over medium heat until tender, about 45 minutes. Drain beans, reserving cooking liquid. Bring 1/2 cup water to boil. Pour over bulgur in bowl. Let stand 30 minutes to soften wheat (the water will be absorbed). Heat olive oil in large saucepan. Add red and white onions and saute until tender. Add garlic, celery and carrots. Saute until glazed. Add chili powder, cumin, cayenne, basil and oregano. Cook over low heat until carrots are almost tender. Add squash, zucchini, peppers and mushrooms and cook 4 minutes. Stir in bulgur, kidney beans, tomatoes and reserved cooking liquid from beans. Cook 30 minutes or until vegetables are tender. Mix tomato paste with white wine until smooth then stir into vegetable mixture. Season to taste with salt and pepper.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(696,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(696,3,'Makes 6 to 8 servings');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(696,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(696,5,'Created by: Gelson''s Markets, Southern California.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(696,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(696,7,'(C) 1992 The Los Angeles Times');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(697,1,'Method: In a large heavy stew pot, place bouillon and 1/2 C white grape juice, onion, green pepper, celery garlic, cook until tender, 5-7 minutes. Add other ingredients, cook over low heat, stirring occasionally to keep from sticking to bottom. Cover and simmer gently until corn and okra are done. (or simmer in crockpot 6-7 hours)');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(697,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(697,3,'Note:  Cut fresh corn from cob with a sharp knife, then scrape the remaining corn off the cob.  Four ears will make about two cups. If you use dried herbs, rub them with the palms of your hands before adding to the pot, this releases their aroma and goodness.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(697,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(697,5,'Exchanges:  1 Veg, 1 Bread, and 107 calories. Update old family favorite - Alice in Houston');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(697,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(697,7,'A.BROADDUS [Alice in Hou]    at 08:55 EDT');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(698,1,'Mix the flour and water to form a paste and set aside.  In a mortar pound together the garlic, coriander root and peppercorns to form a paste.  Heat the oil and briefly fry the garlic paste, then add all the remaining ingredients down to and including the sugar, stirring constantly.  Add the flour and water paste and stir to thicken.  Remove from the heat and leave to cool.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(698,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(698,3,'Drain the beancurd sheets and spread out on a flat surface.  Place a line of the cooled filling along one edge of each sheet and roll to form a long sausage.  Place the 3 sausages in a steamer and steam for 15 minutes. Remove and leave to cool.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(698,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(698,5,'When ready to serve, deep-fry the sausages until golden brown, drain and slice into 1/4-inch (6 mm) rounds and serve on a bed of lettuce and mint leaves with Plum Sauce.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(698,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(698,7,'Source: Thai Vegetarian Cooking by Vatcharin Bhumichitr Typed for you by Karen Mintzias');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,1,'Put mung beans in a bowl with 3 cups water.  Cover lightly and set aside for 12 hours.  Drain beans and wrap in a very damp dish towel.  Put the wrapped bundle in a bowl.  Put this bowl in a dark place (like an unused oven) for 24 hours.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,3,'Wash rice well and soak in 4 cups of water for half an hour.  Drain well.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,5,'Preheat oven to 325 F.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,7,'Heat oil in a wide, heavy, 4- to 5-quart ovenproof pot over a medium-high flame.  When hot, put in mustard seeds.  As soon as the mustard seeds begin to pop (this takes just a few seconds), put in the onion.  Stir and fry for about 5 minutes or until onion turns brown at the edges.  Add the garlic and ginger.  Fry, stirring, for about 1 minute.  Turn heat to medium-low and add the mung beans, rice, string beans, mushrooms, garam masala, ground coriander, and salt.  Stir and saute for about 10 minutes or until rice turns translucent and vegetables are well coated with oil. Add 4 cups hot water and the minced parsley.  Turn heat to a medium-high flame and cook, stirring, for about 5 minutes or until most of the water is absorbed.  (There will be an inch or so of water at the bottom.)  Cover the pot first with aluminum foil, crimping and sealing the edges, and then with its own lid.  Place in heated oven for half an hour.  Fluff up with a fork and serve.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(699,9,'Source: Madhur Jaffrey''s World-of-the-East Vegetarian Cooking Typos by: Karen Mintzias');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(700,1,'SAUCE: Heat 1 cup of the water and add peanut butter, stir and allow to cook for 10 minutes, stirring to prevent sticking, then set aside.  Put the oil into the saucepan, then add the onions and cook for 5 minutes together.  Add all the other sauce ingredients, and the rest of the water (2 1/2 cups) and the peanut sauce.  Stir well and simmer for 20 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(700,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(700,3,'VEGETABLES: Peel the plantain, and slice and fry in hot oil until brownish on both sides.  Drain on paper towels.  Put the butter (or margarine) into a pan, on a moderate heat, saute the carrots, beans and onions for 15 minutes, then serve the vegetables onto plates with the plantains, pour the sauce over the vegetables and garnish with green onions.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(700,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(700,5,'Source: Caribbean and African Cooking, by Rosamund Grant Typos by: Karen Mintzias');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(701,1,'Beat shortening till fluffy.  Add sugar & continue to beat until well combined.  Add the rest of the ingredients in order, beating well after each addition.  When the ingredients are well mixed, wrap the mixture in waxed paper & refrigerate for 1 hour to make the dough easier to handle.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(701,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(701,3,'On a floured board, roll out the dough until it is about an 1/8 inch thick.  Using a cookie cutter, cut into cookies & place on a cookie sheet. Bake 8 to 10 minutes at 275F.  Cool for a couple of minutes on the sheet & then remove to a wire rack to cool.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(701,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(701,5,'Posted by Mark Satterly in Intercook');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,1,'Heat the oil in a large, deep pan.  Add the long-grain brown rice and onion slices and stir until the rice is coated and begins to turn opaque. Add the garlic, saffron, stock or wate, lemon rind and salt and pepper. Mix well, then bring to a boil.  Mix again, to distribute the saffron coloring.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,3,'Arrange the vegetables and olives attractively on top of the rice. Bring to a boil.  Cover with a lid or foil and simmer for 45 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,5,'Sprinkle with parsley and serve straight from the pan.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,7,'May be served with blanched almonds, slivered Brazil nuts or whole cashew nuts- separately, in a bowl - for people to help themselves to if they like.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,9,'Variation: VEGETARIAN PAELLA WITH ARTICHOKES: Use 4 to 6 globe artichokes instead of the leeks.  Very tender baby artichokes can simply be quartered; otherwise cut the leaves and choke from the artichokes, then halve or quarter the artichoke bottoms.  Garnish with artichoke leaves.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,10,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(702,11,'Rose Elliot, "The Complete Vegetarian Cuisine"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(703,1,'Kishke traditionally is prepared by stuffing a seasoned mixture of flour, onion and meat into casings.  This recipe is a flavorful vegetarian version.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(703,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(703,3,'Mix all ingredients in a large bowl.  Spoon half of the mixture onto a piece of aluminum foil and roll into a cylinder.  Repeat with remaining mixture.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(703,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(703,5,'Place cylinders on a cookie sheet or baking pan.  Bake at 350 degrees for 45 minutes.  Turn cylinders upside down and cook for an additional 45 minutes.  Remove and discard foil.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(703,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(703,7,'From an old Vegetarian Times magazine. Uploaded by Nan Blanchard; 73540,700');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,1,'Heat the oil in a large, deep pan.  Add the long-grain brown rice and onion slices and stir until the rice is coated and begins to turn opaque. Add the garlic, saffron, stock or wate, lemon rind and salt and pepper. Mix well, then bring to a boil.  Mix again, to distribute the saffron coloring.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,3,'Arrange the vegetables and olives attractively on top of the rice. Bring to a boil.  Cover with a lid or foil and simmer for 45 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,5,'Sprinkle with parsley and serve straight from the pan.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,7,'May be served with blanched almonds, slivered Brazil nuts or whole cashew nuts- separately, in a bowl - for people to help themselves to if they like.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,9,'Variation: VEGETARIAN PAELLA WITH ARTICHOKES: Use 4 to 6 globe artichokes instead of the leeks.  Very tender baby artichokes can simply be quartered; otherwise cut the leaves and choke from the artichokes, then halve or quarter the artichoke bottoms.  Garnish with artichoke leaves.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,10,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(704,11,'Source: The Complete Vegetarian Cuisine - by Rose Elliot ISBN: 0-394-57123-1 Typed for you by Karen Mintzias');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,1,'Cover mushrooms with hot water and let stand 1 hour.  Drain; cut off stems.  Rinse caps well; squeeze dry.  Cut into 1/8-inch dice.  Set aside.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,3,'Place tofu in large sieve.  Bring 8 cups water to boil.  Pour into metal bowl just larger than sieve.  Place sieve gently in water.  Let tofu soak 30 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,5,'Drain tofu.  Mix mushrooms and preserved vegetable in medium bowl.  Mix 5 tablespoons water and next 8 ingredients in small bowl.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,7,'Heat vegetable oil in wok or heavy large skillet over high heat 1 minute. Add green onions, garlic and ginger and stir-fry 1 minute.  Add mushroom mixture and stir-fry 1 minute.  Stir broth mixture.  Add to wok with peas and stir-fry until sauce boils, about 1 minute.  Add tofu and toss gently to coat with sauce.  Cook 2 1/2 minutes, tossing gently.  Divide between plates.  Sprinkle Szechwan powder over (recipe follows).');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,9,'SZECHWAN PEPPERCORN POWDER:  (Makes about 4 teaspoons) Heat heavy frying pan or wok over medium-low heat 1 minute.  Add 1 tablespoon whole Szechwan peppercorns and stir until aromatic, about 4 minutes.  Transfer to blender.  Cool 10 minutes.  Blend to a fine powder. Store at room temperature.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,10,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(705,11,'Source: Bon Appetit, November 1988. Typed for you by Karen Mintzias');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(706,1,'Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Heat oil in a saucepan and add onion and quinoa. Saute over medium heat, stirring constantly for 3 minutes. Add red bell pepper and saute an additional 2 minutes. Add water, soy sauce and rosemary. (If using fresh peas, add them now.) Bring contents to a boil; cover and simmer 15 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(706,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(706,3,'Meanwhile, roast walnuts in 350 degree oven for 5 minutes. When quinoa is cooked, turn off heat and mix in walnuts and frozen peas. Let set an additional 10 minutes and serve.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(706,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(706,5,'From _Favorite Vegetarian Recipes_ from the Society for Texas Animal Rights. Recipe by John Mackey, CEO, Whole Foods Markets, Austin, Texas.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(706,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(706,7,'DEEANNE [EatMoVeggies]       at 19:13 EDT');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,1,'Wash lentils thoroughly.  Place in pot with the water & bring to a boil over medium heat.  Cook about 10 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,3,'Stir in salt, garlic, chili & mustard.  Lower heat & simmer for 30 minutes till lentils are soft.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,5,'In a skillet, heat the ghee & toss in the cumin seeds & chili powder.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,7,'Top cooked dahl just before serving with ghee mixture.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(707,9,'Michael Pandya, "Indian Vegetarian Cooking"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(708,1,'Boil the potatoes till they are just tender.  Saute the garlic & ginger with the spices for 1 minute & then add the onion.  Saute for a few minutes longer.  Add tomatoes, eggplant & a splash of the water.  Simmer for 10 minutes.  Add the zucchini & peppers & simmer for 20 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(708,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(708,3,'Drain the potatoes, mash roughly & add to the stew.  Add the juice & peanut butter.  Stir well.  Simmer for 5 to 10 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(708,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(708,5,'Serve on rice or millet & garnish with pineapple or banana slices.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(708,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(708,7,'"New Recipes From Moosewood Restaurant"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,1,'Wash rice well in several changes of cold water.  Strain & ensure that all dirt & stones have been removed.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,3,'Combine rice with water.  Add the soy sauce & Worcesterhire sauce.  Bring to a boil, reduce heat.  Cover and simmer for 70 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,5,'Meanwhile, using a skillet, heat the ghee until hot.  Add mushrooms & onion & saute for 2 minutes.  Add the green pepper & continue to saute for another 3 minutes, until the onion is softened.  Toss in the basil & parsley.  Stir & remove from heat.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,7,'When the rice has softened & the water has almost been evaporated, stir in the saute mixture.  Let simmer for another 5 minutes.  Serve.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(709,9,'Posted by Anne Maclellan in Intercook');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(710,1,'Combine the water & soy sauce in a pot & bring to a boil over medium high heat.  Add wild rice & cover, reduce heat & simmer for 30 minutes.  Add the quinoa, cover & simmer for a furtehr 20 minutes or until the water is all absorbed.  Remove from heat & allow to steam, covered for 5 minutes. Fluff with a fork.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(710,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(710,3,'"Quick & Natural Rice Dishes"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(711,1,'PREHEAT OVEN TO 350F. Rinse the wild rice, and soak it in water for a half hour, then drain. Add 4 cups fresh water and salt, and bring to a boil. Cook, covered, at a simmer until the grains are swollen and tender, but still chewy, about 30 to 35 minutes. Pour the cooked rice into a colander and let it drain briefly. While the rice is cooking, toast the hazelnuts in the oven, 7 to 10 minutes, or until they smell toasty. Let them cool a few minutes; then rub them in a small kitchen towel to remove most of the skins. Don''t worry about any flecks of skins that won''t come off. Roughly chop the hazelnuts, leaving the pieces fairly large. Rinse the currants in warm water and squeeze them dry; then cover them with the orange juice and let them soak until needed. Prepare the vinaigrette. Add the soaked currants and the fennel to the warm rice, and toss with the dressing. Just before serving, cut the apple into small pieces, add it to the rice, along with the hazelnuts, and toss. Season with freshly ground black pepper, and additional salt, if needed, and serve.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(711,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(711,3,'Deborah Madison, "Prodigy Guest Chefs Cookbook"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,1,'PRESSURE COOKER: Heat the oil in the cooker.  Add the shallots and celery and cook, stirring frequently, until softened slightly, about 1 minute. Stir in the rice, chestnuts, currants, aniseed, salt, and water.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,3,'Lock the lid in place and over high heat bring to high pressure.  Lower the heat just enough to maintain high pressure and cook for 25 minutes. Allow the pressure to come down naturally or use a quick release method. Remove the lid, tilting it away from you to allow any excess steam to escape.  If the rice or chestnuts are not quite cooked, return to high pressure for a few minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,5,'Drain (reserving the liquid for stock) and return to the pot.  Cover and let steam over low heat for a few minutes to dry out.  Fluff up as you stir in the orange peel.  Break up chestnuts into 2 to 3 pieces with a fork, if desired.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,7,'STANDARD STOVETOP: Soak the chestnuts overnight.  Drain and reserve the water.  In a heavy 2-quart saucepan, heat the oil.  Add the shallots and celery and saute for 1 minute.  Add the chestnut soaking liqiud plus enough water to equal 3 cups and bring to a boil.  Stir in the rice, reserved chestnuts, currants, aniseed, and salt.  Return to the boil, cover, reduce heat, and simmer until most of the grains have butterflied and almost all the liquid has been absorbed, about 50 minutes.  Let stand, covered, off heat for 10 minutes.  If there is still liquid left in the bottom of the pot, lift out the rice with a slotted spoon.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(712,9,'Source: Recipes from an Ecological Kitchen - by Lorna J. Sass ISBN: 0-688-10051-1 Typed by Karen Mintzias');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,1,'FOR CREPES: Blend the egg replacer w/1/2C water until smooth.  Add remaining ingredients and blend one minute at high speed.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,3,'Heat a crepe pan or non stick 8" skillet over low heat, brush the bottom lightly w/oil (I use unrefined corn oil).  When pan is heated, take it off the burner, let cool about three seconds and pour 3-4T batter into it. Swirl the pan so the bottom is coated w/a thin layer of batter.  Put the pan back on the burner and cook until lightly browned.  Flip the crepe and cook until that side is lightly browned as well.  Repeat w/remaining batter.  This makes about a dozen crepes.  Note that you will inevitably screw up the first crepe or two, but it will become fairly routine after that.  Don''t worry about it, I still do that after all these years.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,5,'FOR STUFFING: Saute the onion in a little dry white wine for a minute or two, then add wild rice and stock, cover tightly, bring to a boil, turn heat to low and cook about an hour, until all liquid is absorbed.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,7,'While the rice cooks, saute celery in oil until slightly tender, add onions and all mushrooms, and saute until all vegs are medium tender. Add cooked rice, tomato and seasoning and cook another ten minutes or so.  Fill crepes w/the mixture, roll them over it and heat in a preheated oven at 350 for about ten minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,9,'Serve w/Nutty Almond Sauce and garnish w/parsley and a twisted orange slice.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,10,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,11,'FOR NUTTY ALMOND SAUCE: Toast almonds until golden, then pulverize. (Don''t overgrind or you''ll get almond butter.)');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,12,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,13,'Heat oil a few minutes in a heavy bottomed skillet, then stir in flour and cook 2-3 minutes on low, until fragrant.  Stir in soy milk and continue to stir until it begins to thicken, then stir in seasonings. Cover and cook 10 more minutes, but stir often to prevent scorching. Stir in almonds and cook another 4-5 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,14,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,15,'Serve w/a simple spinach salad w/mustard vinaigrette and French bread, along w/a chilled white wine.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,16,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,17,'From _The_Now_and_Zen_Epicure_ by Miyoko Nishimoto, Summerville, TN, The Book Publishing Co, 1991.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,18,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(713,19,'From: mad4@ellis.uchicago.edu (Bill Maddex)');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(714,1,'In skillet, stir-fry celery, onion, and parsley in ghee for 10 minutes. Blend tofu and water together; add to skillet; also add wild rice, brown rice, lemon juice and rosemary; bring to a boil.  Reduce heat to low and let rice absorb moisture, about 30-40 minutes. Serve.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(714,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(714,3,'Posted by Mark Satterly in Intercook, adapted from a recipe posted by Anne Maclellan');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(715,1,'In a soup pot, saute the bok choy in the oil for 1 minute.  Add the stock & bring to a boil.  Lower the heat & simmer till the bok choy is just tender, about 5 minutes.  Season.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(715,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(715,3,'In a separate pot, bring about 2 quarts of water to a boil.  Drop the wontons into the boiling water & cook til ltender.  Drain & add to the soup.  Serve garnished with scallions.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(715,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(715,5,'"Sundays at Moosewood Restaurant Cookbook"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,1,'Heat peanut oil in a wok.  Sizzle the ginger & garlic briefly then add tofu & stir-fry for a few minutes.  Add scallions, sesame oil & tamari & stir well.  Set aside to cool.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,3,'Set up a work area with wonton wrappers, water & cornstarch.  Place a wrapper in front of you in a diamond position.  Drop a heaping teaspoonful of filling in the centre of the wrapper.  Moisten all 4 edges with water & pull the top corner down to the bottom, folding the wrapper over the filling to make a triangle.  Press edges firmly to make a seal.  Bring left & right corners together above the filling.  Overlap the tips of these corners, moisten with water & press together.  Place completed wrapper on the corn-starch platter & continue till all wrappers are used.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,5,'FOR SOUP: Drop wontons into boiling water & cook for 5 minutes.  Drain.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,7,'TO FRY: Heat 2 to 3 cups of oil in a wok till hot.  Deep fry wontons in batches till golden, 2 to 3 minutes on each side.  Drain.  Serve with dipping sauce or duck sauce.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,8,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,9,'Uncooked wontons will keep in the freezer for a good 2 months if well wrapped.  Thaw before frying, but they can be boiled straight from frozen & cooked 2 minutes longer.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,10,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(716,11,'"Sundays at Moosewood Restaurant Cookbook"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(717,1,'Heat ghee in a skillet.  Saute onion over a medium heat till golden. Reserve some of the onion for garnishing later.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(717,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(717,3,'Add turmeric to the skillet.  Stir & heat briefly.  Add the rest of the spices in order.  Mix well.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(717,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(717,5,'Add the rice & stir a few times.  Pour over water, stir & bring to a boil. Reduce heat, mix in peas & salt, cover & cook for 10 to 15 minutes. Sprinkle with saffron & reserved sauted onion.  Serve hot.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(717,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(717,7,'Michael Pandya, "Indian Vegetarian Cooking"');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,1,'*If black mustard seeds are not available, use 1 Tbs dry mustard.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,2,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,3,'Mix ground mustard powder in with water and allow to sit for 30 minutes.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,4,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,5,'Bring split peas and water to a boil.  Lower heat to medium. Add bay leaves and tumeric (I forgot the tumeric--was good anyway). Simmer, covered, until peas are done, 40 to 45 minutes.  (When pressed between the thumb and the index finger, they break easily.) While simmering, uncover occasionally and stir, adding a Tbs or so of hot water if the mixture sticks to the bottom of the pan.  When cooked, remove and discard bay leaves. Add salt and keep warm.  Heat oil in a small, 6-inch skillet over medium-low heat. Saute ginger root and jalape o until ginger is lightly browned, 1 to 2 minutes. Add mustard paste and cook for another minute, stirring constantly. Add coconut and stir several times. Remove from heat. Pour over the pea mixture and stir. (I had to drain my peas, because I still had lots of water in mine.)  Let stand covered for 15 minutes. Add a dab of soy margarine if desired and garnish with cilantro. (I didn''t use the cilantro)');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,6,'');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,7,'I think this would make a good filling for pita pockets. I didn''t think the peas were "zesty" enough, so I sprinkled hot pepper vinegar on mine.');
INSERT INTO instruction VALUES(718,8,'');
